[2] Feline, human exposure - New Jersey
Date: Sat 28 Jul 2012
Source: Manalapan Patch [edited]
http://manalapan.patch.com/articles/rabid-cat-attacks-3-manalapan-residents


The Manalapan Township Health Department and Western Monmouth Animal Control are alerting residents about an outdoor stray cat that tested positive for rabies on 25 Jul 2012.

The black and white cat, which was found in the area of Atrium Way and Chestnut Way off of Pension Road, bit 3 residents on 2 separate occasions on Wed 25 Jul 2012. The cat was captured and sent out to be tested for rabies; the positive results came back on 27 Jul 2012.

The people who were bitten by the cat have now begun a rabies post-exposure prophylaxis treatment.

Anyone who has come into contact with this stray cat is advised to call the Manalapan Health Department, located within the Manalapan Township Municipal Building.

Also, if a pet has come into contact with the feline please get in touch with your veterinarian, the Health Department advises.

According to Manalapan Health Department Director David Richardson, the incident of the rabid cat is not related to a recent event involving a rabid bat that was discovered in the township. Please be on the lookout for any other animals or cats that may be acting strangely. Unusual behavior in animals is generally defined as aggressive tendencies, a sick appearance, or a very lethargic or passive behavior, according to the Health Department. Any observances of peculiar functioning in animals should be reported to the Manalapan Health Department or the Police Department after normal working hours or on the weekends at the after hours number.

The Health Department wants to take this opportunity to remind residents that all of their domestic pets should be properly vaccinated against the rabies virus.

